<br>
As the ship leaves earth, it would be as folded up as possible, to minimize moments on the frame.  The inital propulsion would be a flow through nuclear - hydrogen or ammonia, (maybe nerva) with turbopumps driven by F-1s (I really don't know, just trying to work this out).  This would get it out of the Earth-moon system, and headed for the asteroid belt.  <br>
<br>
Heres where the fun begins (I hope)  the craft unfurls, lands on the asteroid, locks itself to the surface, and the basic idea is that one half - i guess the front - becomes a drilling rig for, well, dirt.  Ok carbon, Iron, whatever this thing is made out of.  By the way, if Armageddon (possibly the worst movie ever made) is right, then Iron may not be the best choice.  I might get picky and look for something loosely packed, like sandstone kinda rock.  <br>
<br>
Now the front end will have several TBMs to cut into the surface of the asteroid, working from the inside out, a convoluted conveyor and bore setup will try to keep the upper section supplied with enough power to get this thing somewhere.<br>
<br>
In the middle, the rock coming up from TBMs is further Processed, making it as fine as possible, then is passed up the ladder to the propulsion section.<br>
<br>
Now, maybe as much as 100 feet above the surface of the asteroid, the pulverized (i mean nearly dust, not just gravel).  Here this dust is sent into an enclosed centripedal wheel, it enters at the center, and is flung to the outside, just like in a car turbocharger.  it gets shot around, pinned to the outside of the wheel's enclosure, until it reaches the opening, at which time it would be vented to space, driving the spacecraft - I mean asteroidcraft - ahead. <br>
<br>
Oh yeah, how is this related to nuclear other than the NERVA inital stage? Glad you asked, the centripedal flow &quot;dirt turbine&quot; gets it's power from a rather common nuclear powerplant, similar to those found today on land, and also in the Navy's Carriers and Submarines.  Just a straight reduction geared turbine powering the wheel.  And of course all the propulsion would be closed loop, which would keep our &quot;vaccum heads&quot; (ahem AHEM- greenies, tree huggers, and other people who whine about radition being dumped into a radiation filled vacuum).  <br>
And also by having closed loop, the power from the reactor can be routed to electrical power turbines, a form of Nerva heater (LH2 in, with heat right off reactor - cold reactor coolant and acceleration + warm LH2 out), or to drive the propulsion wheels.<br>
<br>
